<h2 id="internship-challenge-question-1">Internship Challenge Question 1</h2>
<p>Part (a) The average order value (AOV) has be identified as $3145.13. The has been determined by taking the average of the order_amount field from the data. Most applications for taking the average of a group of data points assumes its distribution to be Gaussian (or normal). In this data set we have a handful of orders that are several orders of magnitude greater than even the average. These outliers can be visualized in the histogram below.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1" aria-hidden="true"></a>d<span class="op">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(order_amount))<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>()</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p>Another factor that could be influencing the high average value is the distribution of sales at shops. If there is one shop that sells a lot of shoes at a high value then this will increase the average. It was determined that the sales amongst the shops was uniformly distributed (based on inspection of the histogram below) and that the only contributory factor to the large average order value is the outliers in the data.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb3"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><a href="#cb3-1" aria-hidden="true"></a>d<span class="op">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb3-2"><a href="#cb3-2" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(shop_id))<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">binwidth =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p>Part (b) If the task is to evaluate the AOV of sales from the past 30 days we will have weight the amount of each order by the total number of items ordered. By doing so we are making an assumption that each item within an order is identically priced. The median is a more appropriate metric for identifying the value of the most frequent order. The median of the order_amount is $284. That means that half of all transactions is greater than $284 and while the other half is less than $284. Another solution to better understand the distribution of data is to remove the outliers. One method to evaluate the outliers is to use the Zscore. Zscore evaluates each data point and determines the number of standard deviations away from the mean. While the mean is suspect given, evaluation of zscore provides a statistical argument for omitting outliers.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb4"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1"><a href="#cb4-1" aria-hidden="true"></a>d[d<span class="op">$</span>order_amount<span class="op">&lt;</span><span class="dv">4000</span>,]<span class="op">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb4-2"><a href="#cb4-2" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(order_amount))<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>()</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p>Part (c) The AOV of the unprocessed data is $3145 which is well beyond 99% of the order amount of each record. I will therefore omit all data that has a zscore &gt;0. This means that all records whose value is less than the mean will be evaluated for the AOV calculation.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1" aria-hidden="true"></a>d&lt;-d<span class="op">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb6-2"><a href="#cb6-2" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">mutate</span>(<span class="dt">zscore =</span> (order_amount <span class="op">-</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">mean</span>(order_amount))<span class="op">/</span><span class="kw">sd</span>(order_amount) )</span>
<span id="cb6-3"><a href="#cb6-3" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(<span class="kw">paste</span>(<span class="st">&quot;The number of records whose value is less than the mean is&quot;</span>,<span class="kw">sum</span>(d<span class="op">$</span>order_amount<span class="op">&lt;</span><span class="dv">3145</span>)<span class="op">/</span><span class="dv">5000</span><span class="op">*</span><span class="dv">100</span>,<span class="st">&quot;%&quot;</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;The number of records whose value is less than the mean is 98.74 %&quot;
</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb8"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1"><a href="#cb8-1" aria-hidden="true"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(<span class="kw">paste</span>(<span class="st">&quot;The adjusted AOV is&quot;</span>,<span class="kw">mean</span>(d<span class="op">$</span>order_amount[d<span class="op">$</span>zscore<span class="op">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>])))</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;The adjusted AOV is 302.580514482479&quot;
</code></pre>
<p>As displayed, the adjusted AOV is $303 which is close to the median original median of $284.</p>
